<h3>Context</h3>
<p>
    This research grounds the <a href="/projects/webreliability/">Web Reliability</a> standard's design
    decisions by surveying how established frameworks implement retry strategies, circuit breakers,
    offline queuing, and HTTP error classification. The goal is to identify which patterns are
    HTTP-specific (and therefore belong in adapter implementations) versus universally applicable
    (and therefore belong in the protocol contract).
</p>

<h3>Framework Survey</h3>

<h4>TanStack Query</h4>
<table>
    <tr><th>API</th><th>What it does</th><th>Applicability</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>retry</code> (number | fn)</td><td>Max retry count; or a predicate <code>(failureCount, error) =&gt; boolean</code></td><td>Universal — predicate pattern directly maps to <code>tryRecover</code> returning null</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>retryDelay</code> (number | fn)</td><td>Delay before next attempt; fn receives attempt count</td><td>Universal — maps to <code>RecoveryResult.delay</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>networkMode: 'online'</code></td><td>Pauses queries when <code>navigator.onLine</code> is false</td><td>HTTP / network specific — an offline-queue handler concern, not the protocol</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>onError</code> callback</td><td>Notification after final failure</td><td>Universal — maps to consumer's post-recovery hook</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>axios-retry</h4>
<table>
    <tr><th>API</th><th>What it does</th><th>Applicability</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>retries</code></td><td>Max retry count</td><td>Universal</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>retryCondition</code> (fn)</td><td>Predicate <code>(error) =&gt; boolean</code> — mirrors <code>tryRecover</code> null vs result</td><td>Universal — the predicate shape directly inspired the null-means-decline decision</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>exponentialDelay</code></td><td>Built-in backoff helper</td><td>HTTP handler specific — belongs in an adapter</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Interceptor composition</td><td>Attaches retry logic at the Axios interceptor layer</td><td>HTTP specific — not a protocol concern</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>urql retryExchange</h4>
<table>
    <tr><th>API</th><th>What it does</th><th>Applicability</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>initialDelayMs</code> / <code>maxDelayMs</code></td><td>Backoff range</td><td>Universal — maps to <code>RecoveryResult.delay</code> computation</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>randomDelay</code> (jitter)</td><td>Randomises delay to prevent thundering herd</td><td>Universal — jitter is a best practice for any distributed system retry</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>maxNumberAttempts</code></td><td>Cap</td><td>Universal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Exchange pipeline</td><td>Composable middleware chain around operations</td><td>GraphQL-specific mechanism — informed the first-that-accepts registry pattern</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>SWR</h4>
<table>
    <tr><th>API</th><th>What it does</th><th>Applicability</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>onErrorRetry</code> callback</td><td>Full control over retry logic; called with error + key + config + revalidate + info</td><td>Universal — closest model to the handler receiving context and deciding outcome</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>errorRetryCount</code></td><td>Max retries</td><td>Universal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Pause on offline</td><td>Stops retrying when <code>navigator.onLine</code> is false</td><td>Network specific</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Apollo RetryLink</h4>
<table>
    <tr><th>API</th><th>What it does</th><th>Applicability</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>delay.initial</code> / <code>delay.max</code> / <code>delay.jitter</code></td><td>Exponential backoff with jitter</td><td>Universal backoff parameters</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>attempts.retryIf</code> (fn)</td><td>Predicate receiving operation + error</td><td>Universal — predicate pattern reinforces null-means-decline</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Link chain</td><td>Wraps operations; composable layers</td><td>GraphQL-specific — informed registry-as-chain thinking</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Key Design Decisions Informed by This Research</h3>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Decision</th><th>Evidence from frameworks</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>null-means-decline</strong> over a separate <code>canHandle()</code></td>
            <td>axios-retry's <code>retryCondition</code> and Apollo's <code>retryIf</code> both use a single predicate function that returns true/false. Combining predicate + action into one <code>tryRecover()</code> removes the two-step call pattern.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Registry, not a dedicated chain object</strong></td>
            <td>urql and Apollo use exchange/link chains, but these are framework-specific pipeline constructs. <code>CustomRegistry.values()</code> already provides ordered iteration — no new abstraction needed.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>HTTP-specific logic stays in handlers, not the protocol</strong></td>
            <td>Every framework ties backoff math, status-code classification, and Retry-After handling to its HTTP transport. These are not universal — a database timeout handler has no HTTP status code to inspect. The protocol carries only what any operation type needs: the raw Error and attempt count.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Jitter is a best practice, not a default</strong></td>
            <td>urql and Apollo both offer jitter as opt-in. Jitter prevents thundering herd in distributed systems — relevant for HTTP adapters, overkill for local computation retries. Handlers that know their domain add jitter; the protocol does not mandate it.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong><code>RecoveryContext.attempt</code> is 1-based</strong></td>
            <td>TanStack Query, SWR, and urql all pass attempt/failure count to retry predicates. 1-based is more natural for humans reading logs ("attempt 3 of 3") and avoids off-by-one in exponential backoff formulas (<code>2^(attempt-1)</code> yields 1, 2, 4 starting at attempt 1).</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Resilience Composition — How Multiple Concerns Cooperate</h3>
<p>
    The single-handler libraries above each ship <em>one</em> retry mechanism, so they never answer the
    question the <a href="/projects/webreliability/">Web Reliability</a> protocol must:
    when a circuit breaker, a retry, and an offline queue all apply to one operation, how do they
    <strong>compose</strong>? The canonical prior art lives outside the JS data-fetching world — in the
    two most authoritative resilience libraries — and both give the same answer.
</p>
<table>
    <tr><th>Library</th><th>Composition model</th><th>What it establishes</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Polly</strong> <code>PolicyWrap</code> (.NET)</td>
        <td>Combines Retry / CircuitBreaker / Timeout / Fallback / Bulkhead into one executable policy, innermost→outermost, left-to-right, in an <strong>author-chosen order</strong>.</td>
        <td>Composition is an <strong>explicit, ordered wrap</strong> — never implicit. And the order is load-bearing: Polly's own guidance is <code>CircuitBreaker</code>-wraps-<code>Retry</code> for short/no delays (don't let close-spaced tries trip the breaker), but <code>WaitAndRetry</code>-wraps-<code>CircuitBreaker</code> for long delays (circuit state can change during the wait). <strong>Both orderings are correct in different timing regimes.</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>resilience4j</strong> (Java)</td>
        <td>Higher-order <strong>decorators</strong> (<code>CircuitBreaker</code>, <code>Retry</code>, <code>RateLimiter</code>, <code>Bulkhead</code>) stacked over a functional interface; you stack more than one, order explicit.</td>
        <td>Same shape — cooperation = the author <strong>explicitly stacks</strong> decorators. No framework auto-orchestrates resilience concerns into a fixed order.</td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>
    <strong>Design consequence:</strong> a baked protocol-level orchestration would have to pick
    breaker-wraps-retry <em>or</em> retry-wraps-breaker — and Polly proves both are right in different
    regimes, so baking either is wrong. WE's analogue is therefore a <strong>composite handler</strong>
    the app authors and orders (a handler that holds and sequences sub-handlers), with the protocol
    staying single-dispatch (first-that-accepts). This reinforces the existing
    <em>registry-not-chain</em> decision rather than reopening it.
</p>

<h3>Recovery-State Surfacing — Phase, Not Just Status</h3>
<p>
    The protocol's other under-surveyed seam is how the active recovery state reaches the UI. The prior
    art shows the recovery <em>phase</em> is a vocabulary distinct from the data status, normalized at
    the library, not invented per call site.
</p>
<table>
    <tr><th>Source</th><th>Surfacing model</th><th>What it establishes</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>TanStack Query</strong></td>
        <td>Splits <code>status</code> (<code>pending</code>/<code>error</code>/<code>success</code> — the <em>data</em>) from <code>fetchStatus</code> (<code>fetching</code>/<code>paused</code>/<code>idle</code> — the <em>recovery/network phase</em>), plus a derived <code>isPaused</code>.</td>
        <td>The industry already separates "what is the data" from "what is recovery doing now." An offline-and-waiting query is <code>success</code>+<code>paused</code>, not a new error. Precedent for a recovery-<strong>phase</strong> vocabulary kept separate from the data/loader status.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>Circuit-breaker canon</strong></td>
        <td>Three states <code>CLOSED → OPEN → HALF-OPEN</code> (probing).</td>
        <td>"Circuit open" is a recovery <em>phase</em>, not a terminal failure — the operation isn't being attempted now but may recover on the next probe. The UX must distinguish it from <code>failed</code>, so the page's current <code>recovering</code>/<code>fallback</code>/<code>failed</code> needs a finer phase discriminator.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h3>Open Questions (resolved into decision <a href="/backlog/1032-design-the-protocol-level-error-recovery-seam-for-webreliabi/">#1032</a>)</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Classification:</strong> does the contract carry a normalized failure <em>disposition</em> (<code>transient</code>/<code>terminal</code>/<code>deferred</code>) the UX reads, or stay fully handler-private? (Supersedes the earlier "operation category in <code>RecoveryContext</code>" framing — the disposition is the <em>output</em> of classification, not the raw logic.)</li>
    <li><strong>Surfacing:</strong> a normalized recovery-<em>phase</em> discriminator (<code>retrying</code>/<code>queued</code>/<code>awaiting-manual</code>/<code>circuit-open</code>) on the in-flight state, or leave the active-recovery vocabulary to each consumer?</li>
    <li><strong>Composition:</strong> strict single-dispatch + author-composed composite handler (the Polly/resilience4j model), or a protocol-level cooperative continuation model?</li>
    <li>Settled by the original survey: backoff math + jitter stay handler-owned; the contract carries only the opaque resolved <code>delay</code>.</li>
</ul>
